##"comrade-in-arms becomes patient" of Wuhan Doctor: We are afraid, retreat, how does Wuhan Do?

Wechat, boyangcongpeople

The function introduces, peels off the human shell, records the real sensible life. Presented by the in-depth Reporting Department of the Beijing News.

Now it would be nice to have a few more N95 masks and donate some non-invasive breathing machines to our hospital.

Choi Ngai in protective clothing. Photo by interviewee

By Zhou Xiaoqi, Beijing News

Editor | Xiao Shu Chen proofread | Xu Li Yang

The text is about 2,456 words long and takes about five minutes to read

In the early hours of February 2,2020, an article by a leading physician in Wuhan was widely circulated. The writer, Cai Yi, director of the Pain Department at Wuhan Central Hospital (Houhu district) , described the experience of first-line nurses being infected, and urged everyone to do a good job of self-isolation, do not disappoint the doctor's tears.

The hospital was the closest to the south China seafood market and one of the first to admit COVID-19 patients.

On January 22, after the hospital was requisitioned as the second set of designated hospitals, Cai Yi and the infected nurses volunteered to support the front line.

The nurse's infection upset Cai Yi. But the battle continued, "we are afraid, retreat, Wuhan how to do? "

"Not only to treat the sick, but to protect those around them who might be infected. "

Peeling onion: You wrote in the friend circle that a nurse in your department was infected. What happened?

Cai Yi: The infected nurses and I were the first ones to register for the front line on January 23, the same day we entered the ward. We work hard, eight to ten hours a day, and nurses have more contact with patients than we do. The day before yesterday I suddenly received a phone call from her, where she was crying, said he was infected. I rushed over to see her CT scan, which showed a familiar white spot on her lung. I didn't know what to do to comfort her.

Peel the onion: How's she doing?

Cai Yi: She is isolated at home now, take a few antivirals, but the effect is not very good, I am considering to admit her to hospital. Her parents went for a CT scan, and dad's lungs showed an infection, so maybe they'll take him in, too.

Peeling onions: How did your colleagues react to the news of her infection?

Cai Yi: some colleagues know, began to go around her. Well, technically, I'm supposed to go around it, too, but I can't. She said she still has parents at home, for fear of infection, want to rent their own house isolation, I added a mask, accompanied her to our concentration in the home hotel check out, and then behind her back to the organization report, they arranged for her to disinfection of the residence.

As a rule, contact with her is supposed to be a 14-day quarantine, but there's no way. We still have 32 patients. All this time I've been cheering up my colleagues, encouraging them, not only to treat patients, but also to keep an eye out for fellow soldiers who might be infected.

Adequate quantity and poor quality of protective equipment

Peeling an onion: what's your day job like now?

Cai Yi: I am the director of the pain department. I will be in charge of the ward that our department is responsible for. I will be responsible for the whole course of patients'diagnosis and treatment. I will treat patients, prescribe drugs, and so on. I will go to the ward inspection every morning and evening. My working hours will add up to about 10 hours.

Peeling onion: what is the general situation of Your Ward?

Cai Yi: our Ward is the second district with fever. There are 32 patients in total. Most of them are over 40 years old.

From the hardware point of view, this ward used to be an oncology ward, with single rooms and double rooms. After being used temporarily to treat patients suffering from infectious diseases, some alterations were made, but there's no way to meet strict quarantine standards all at once.

From the personnel point of view, we are quite adequate, our pain department medical staff have come, there are 12 doctors, 30 nurses, so we can still achieve a normal schedule, according to their physical conditions, who will not overload work.

Cai Yi and his team work in protective clothing. Photo courtesy of the respondents

Peeling the onion: are the supplies secure?

Cai Yi: the quantity of protective equipment still can satisfy, but the comparison that accords with quality requirement is deficient. Usually good with good, no good, we put two not so good together, try to enhance the protection.

We also launched an announcement of material donation to the community, everyone was very active, a citizen had prepared 20 N95 masks before the outbreak, knowing that I would be on the line, he gave me 10, he said to me, "we don't get out much. You paramedics could use it. ".

"patient can't ring the Bell to save us the trouble. "

Peeling an onion: what problems did you run into during this time?

Cai Yi: on the night of January 27, I was on duty for the first time. Our Ward had just opened. A few hours after I entered the ward, the patients were already full. At that time, I was not really prepared mentally or physically. Because everything is strange, strange patients, strange diseases, strange environment.

As I got used to it, I realized that the key issue was the disease itself. The virus is more difficult to control, the incubation period will be infectious, easy to let people off the hook, and the patient's condition changes quickly every day, may be mild today, will be aggravated tomorrow, especially for older people with underlying diseases, the risk is high.

Then there is wearing protective clothing to work, there are many inconvenience, protective glasses often fog, people standing a few meters away from us, we can not see, communication only by shouting at the throat, but also give us some difficulties in communication with patients. But Professor Yang Dong of Concorde Hospital taught me a trick, plus the Wechat of patients and their families, to pull them into different groups, group management, so that we can communicate at any time.

Peeling onions: What is the patient's attitude toward you?

Cai Yi: these 32 patients have given us the greatest support and understanding, and I am very grateful to them. Even endure the discomfort and fear of illness so as not to bother us. A lot of symptoms, we ask out, did not go to rounds, even breathing, they are trying not to say, do not ring the bell. Because they don't want us to be tired. They don't want us to get sick.

Peeling onions: Are there any patients who impress you?

Cai Yi: this morning, I treated a critical male patient, who is in his 60s. I remember the day he took over the ward, he drove to see the doctor by himself. He had been parked near the hospital since he got into the isolation ward. He was already in respiratory failure when he arrived, had been in the ward for nearly a week, and was in a critical condition in the morning, and had not made it through despite the emergency treatment.

After he died, the funeral home car came and took his body straight to the crematorium. His son is still in the United States, his wife and brother did not come to see the last time, crying. Then I helped him drive it home and disinfect it. I'm really sorry about this patient.

"I just want to be worthy of my 'white leather' . "

Peeling the onion: Since when did you become aware of the severity of this outbreak?

Cai Yi: Our hospital is the closest to the south China seafood market. We admitted patients as early as the end of December last year. But the rest of the hospital, especially the surgical department where I work, wasn't very clear about the situation, the whole hospital was so big, there were thousands of staff.

In early January, I read that some people said the virus was similar to SARS, and some of my colleagues started showing symptoms related to pneumonia, but winter itself was the season for viral colds, and no one took it seriously. So it wasn't until Jan. 20, when Zhong Nanshan said on television that the virus could be passed from person to person, that we realized it could be very contagious.

Peeling the onion: YOU'RE A surgeon. Have you ever treated a patient with an infectious disease?

Cai Yi: No, I was still in medical school when SARS happened. But this time, when the hospital issued a surgical mobilization order on January 23, I volunteered.

Peeling an onion: How do you feel after you sign up?

Cai Yi: the doctor also can be afraid, but at this time only have to encourage each other, face difficulty, we are afraid, retreat, how does Wuhan Do? I told my office that a doctor who doesn't touch an outbreak once in his life is like a soldier who has never carried a gun in his life. We just want to be worthy of this "white skin" on the body.
